{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/shortest-paths-directed-acyclic-digraphs","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h3 id=\"table-of-contents\"><a href=\"#table-of-contents\" aria-label=\"table of contents permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Table of Contents</h3>\n<ol>\n<li><a href=\"#motivation\">Motivation</a></li>\n<li><a href=\"#logic\">Logic</a></li>\n</ol>\n<p>In this post, I'll assume you have sufficient <a href=\"/topological-sort\">topological sort</a> knowledge</p>\n<h3 id=\"motivation\"><a href=\"#motivation\" aria-label=\"motivation permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Motivation</h3>\n<p>Turns out, if our graph has no cycles, we can use topological sort to find single source shortest paths even when negative weights are present (Dijkstra's cannot handle negative weights).</p>\n<h3 id=\"logic\"><a href=\"#logic\" aria-label=\"logic permalink\" class=\"anchor\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Logic</h3>\n<p>The idea behind this algorithm is simple:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Initialize <code class=\"language-text\">dist[s]</code> to 0 and all other <code class=\"language-text\">dist[]</code> values to infinity</li>\n<li>Then instead of using weights of edges like we did in Dijkstra's, use topological sort generated sequence to relax the edges. </li>\n</ul>\n<p>Let's start with this graph that has no cycles:</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 676px;\"\n    >\n      <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 57.396449704142015%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"Directed-Graph\"\n        title=\"Directed-Graph\"\n        src=\"/static/62bd2d3da090d5e59ab774446e5b79b0/5a757/spdag1.png\"\n        srcset=\"/static/62bd2d3da090d5e59ab774446e5b79b0/27f03/spdag1.png 173w,\n/static/62bd2d3da090d5e59ab774446e5b79b0/376d0/spdag1.png 345w,\n/static/62bd2d3da090d5e59ab774446e5b79b0/5a757/spdag1.png 676w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 676px) 100vw, 676px\"\n        style=\"width:100%;height:100%;margin:0;vertical-align:middle;position:absolute;top:0;left:0;\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n    </span> <a href=\"https://graphonline.ru/en/\">Image Credit - Directed Graph</a></p>","timeToRead":1,"excerpt":"Table of Contents Motivation Logic In this post